<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96946923819975></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96946923819975><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96946923819975>RE: Druid soloing</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96946923819975#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=759><span id=Scholar>Adiemus</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>63 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Sep 20th 1:00 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.26]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Not knowing what race you are, I can only offer suggestions based on the possible druid starting races.<br><br>First off, soloing will be fairly difficult until you get SoW at 14. Wherever you choose to fight, your first spell should be to damage shield yourself- you'll have to melee alot, so be prepared. Next, snare your target, then DoT him with Flame Lick before DD'ing him with your lightning spell.<br><br>If a wood elf, Orc Hill just north of Kelethin is your best bet for now, though xp will be a bit slow at level 10. Crushbone is a more attractive destination, but remember that you'll be just above orc pawns on the food chain, and trains of reds will be frequent. If you can get into a group down by the slavers' huts or perhaps on Trainer Hill, you'll do very well. If determined to solo, look for the centurions near the zone so you can escape from the trains. Butcherblock is a good alternative, but stay near the zone or the various dwarven guard outposts.<br><br>If playing a halfling, Misty Thicket can be your home until your mid-teens. At 10, hunt scarabs and spders near the gate in the Wall. Plenty of deputies are around to bail you out if you get in over your head. Closer to 14, you can do the goblin or orc camps, pulling with harmony. Or get a partner and do them now- tank or caster with pet is your best bet as a partner. I consider Misty Thicket to be the best newbie zone in the game, so milk it for all its worth.<br><br>If you chose a human in Qeynos, Blackburrow with a group is the best bet I can offer. Trains here are murderous, so soloing is impractical. If soloing is your choice, hunt spiders and such near the guard towers in West Karana. Stay near the Qeynos Hills end of the zone, because werewolves and hill giants do wander the zone.<br><br>If you chose a human in Freeport, hunt sand scarabs and giant spiders (maybe still orc raiders too) in the Desert of North Ro. NRo is vastly preferable to the Commons due to less characters camping it (an exception to this might be the orc camp in West Commons- its generally not camped- though you'll have to contend with giants and griffons that wander the zone. Again, you'd need a group here rather than attempt to solo it). If you choose NRo, stay near the sand-grass border rather than venture too far out into the desert. There's a guard nearby that will help you out if you can make it back to him. Should you choose to group rather than solo, there are three Dervish Cutthroat camps here that offer really good xp at levels up to 15 or so- derv camp three (along the east wall almost to the Oasis of Marr zone) will most likely be your first camp.<br><br>I did try to gently nudge you toward grouping rather than soloing. Once you get to 14 and get SoW, soloing will be much easier and the possibilities for hunting will grow exponentially. Until that time, grouping is a much safer alternative. Either way, you made a great choice picking a druid, and you'll have much enjoyment playing one.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
