	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Sep 16th 6:50 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.60]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There is no real faction with respect to most animals, and certainly not normal ones like wolves, bears and lions., so druids don't lose faction by killing them. Personally, I consider it very poor roleplaying for a druid to kill any sort of normal animal, so I refrain from doing so. If a newbie is being killed by one, I'll snare the critter so the newbie can run (I'll kill the critter if the newbie is on the verge of death), but I try not to directly cause the death of the animal.<br><br>Abominations, such as griffons, are quite another story. I don't consider them normal, naturally-evolving animals, so they're fair game.<br><br>I do also recall reading somewhere that one of the benefits of being a druid is that no normal animal will attack you, as they are fond of doing to most characters while they are resting, healing or medding. <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
