<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=968630784536></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f968630784536><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=968630784536>Newest and best strategy for Casters -- Medding is no longer</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=968630784536#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Sep 10th 8:06 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The new ability to med with a single key has provided a new strategy. Notice that while you med, the mana increases by ticks. Between ticks (5-6seconds) nothing happens. So between ticks you can do something. Anything look, run, heal, track, check persona. Just get medding again before 5 seconds is up. <br><br>I use this as follows. I have "Spells" as a hotkey (number 4), and Heal as a hotkey (number 2). After a kill, I will med immediately, then when I have enough mana, I watch the "ticks" immediately after a tick, Ill hit 4, then 2, I heal, and immediately hit 4 again. Just after I sit, I get the next tick.<br><br>If you want to get somewhere dont run and get there then med. Start by medding when the tick occurs hit spells, run for 4 seconds then hit spells again. Keep doing this until you get to where you were going and you have lost no med time.<br><br>This is the greatest time saver of all time!<br><br>If Verant stop this, ill quit the game.<br><br>Dubrave<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96882833229366></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96882833229366><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96882833229366>Sorry but you're wrong</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96882833229366#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Sep 13th 2:58 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The tick is meaningless.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is provided by the client to give you an estimation of how much mana you have.  What you are doing is fooling the client into thinking you're medding more than you are.  However the server knows your mana and will reset it when you cast your first spell.  This is why if you use your method and then cast something like snare it will appear as if snare took a bub of mana.  What's happening is that the client is being updated by the server with your real mana % instead of the tricked out mana % it thinks it has.  The point is that the server is the thing that sets what mana you have and it's always going to know where you're at regardless of what you do to the client.<br><br>.anonymous.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
