<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96795523310592></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96795523310592><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96795523310592>RE: Level 34 group/solo</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96795523310592#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=759><span id=Scholar>Adiemus</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>63 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Sep 3rd 12:27 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Truth to tell, Minyan, Rathe Mountains is where I intend to go once I hit 34. I'm not sure that you can solo a hill giant at 34, but I know you can team with another class and do so. That new DoT makes a difference.<br><br>I am not very familiar with the Kunark zones, so I can't bring much to the discussion about them, other than many of them are designed for characters in the mid-30s and up. I hunted Dreadlands a couple times with my low 30s paladin and a friend who had a mid-30s druid. Pretty much everything there was yellow or red to us, save for the yeti. The yeti were easy kills, but the zone had quite a few wandering nasties like drachnids that wanted to jump in and were aggro to everyone. Drachnids have VERY serious poison and hit about as hard as a cyclops. I think they're also casters- at least some of them are. The point of this is that I just didn't enjoy my time in Kunark at all.<br><br>As far as the 'old' zones:<br><br> You can still get xp and great loot from the gnolls in SK up to 36. <br><br>If giants and griffons are more your speed, I'd suggest NK, as you rarely have to deal with more than a single giant/griff at a time, and nothing else will aggro on you at that level.<br><br> Sand giants (and the elusive Ancient Cyclops) in South Ro are also a good choice- you can port directly into the zone (as you can in NK as well) and they aren't camped nearly as much here as they are in Oasis. <br><br>Speaking of Oasis, sand giants and spectres are on the menu there. Tough to get a single spectre pull here, though, so grouping might be a better idea. <br><br>I think there is a single spectre in the Innothule Swamp that is soloable, though I prefer not to take on casters- tough to kite them if they keep Fearing you (makes you wonder who is kiting whom). <br><br>Unrest and Trainmore, err...Mistmoor, are also possibilites. Unrest is a personal favorite for several reasons, not the least among them is that it is considered an outdoor zone (SoW and wolf form work here!), as well as the fact that the Undead and their friends (terrors and werebats) WILL NOT aggro a druid in wolf form! The only things that will be higher level than you are the Dwarven Ghost and the gnome necro (don't mess with him- he is nasty. Makes Meldrath positively huggable). i know that it is possible to pull a single MoB at a time and kite it without others joining in- I've seen it done alot. If the zone has anyone at all in it, I guarantee that one person will be a high-level druid camping the Ghost for Dwarven Work Boots (800-1200pp). The Ghost still gives xp at level 50 (so says a buddy of mine). Mistmoor is another matter. I read somewhere that the Undead here would not aggo on you in wolf form either. I found it not to be true- even greens jumped me as I headed toward the house and I had a real nice train to zone. If you can get a good group, the loot is outstanding and the xp constant all the way to low 40s.<br><br>Finally, i know that the Guks fall into this level range, though I have never hunted in either. With the notable exception of Unrest, I prefer to hunt the Great Outdoors- it's where we druids shine.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
